      "FacilityID": 1000061403,
      "SummaryText": "A.  Accidental release prevention and emergency response policies:\r\nAt the North America facility, there are four chemicals covered by the EPA RMP regulation (40 CFR Part 68).  They are: Acrylonitrile, 1-3 Butadiene, Chlorine and Propylene Oxide.  It is vital to observe certain safety precautions in handling these chemicals to prevent unnecessary human exposure, to reduce the threat to personal health and safety of ourselves, our co-workers, our contractors, the community and our environment.  It is our policy to adhere to all Federal and State rules and regulations.  Safety depends on the manner in which we handle these chemicals combined with the safety devices inherent in the design of our facility, as well as the safe handling procedures that we use to train our personnel.\r\n\r\nThe facility maintains an emergency response plan that defines the steps the facility and each employee should take during an accidental release of a regulated substance.  The plan includes both evacuation and protective action procedures for employees not directly involved in the response, and actions to be taken by employees responsible for responding to and mitigating the release.  All employees are trained in the applicable emergency response procedures.  Drills and exercises are routinely conducted to test the facility plans and revise the plans if necessary. \r\nThe emergency response plan also includes procedures for notifying facility personnel, including emergency response personnel, the local Channels Industry Mutual Aid (CIMA) agency, the Community Awareness Emergency Response (CAER) organization and the Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC).  \r\n\r\nB.  The stationary source and regulated substances handled:\r\n\r\nThe Kaneka North America facility is one stationary source with three distinct PSM covered operating units: The Modifiers Unit, Chlorinated-polyvinylchloride (CPVC Unit)and Modified Silicones (MSA Unit).\r\n \r\nThe Modifiers unit handles two RMP-covered chemicals: \r\n+  1, 3-B"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 1000061403,
      "SummaryText": "utadiene\r\n+  Acrylonitrile\r\nThe primary purpose of the Modifiers Unit is to create a polymer which is blended with plastics, such as PVC, for impact improvement and weather resistance.  The product is used in applications for window frames and siding.\r\n\r\nCPVC handles one RMP-covered chemical: \r\n+  Chlorine \r\nChlorine is reacted in a water slurry with the PVC.  The resultant CPVC powder is conveyed to railcar for shipping.  CPVC is used in the manufacturing of hot water plastic pipes.  \r\n\r\nMSA handles one RMP-covered chemical:\r\n+  Propylene oxide\r\nPropylene Oxide (PO) is brought onsite by tank truck and reacted with other organic chemicals to make a modified silicone liquid.  The end product is used in the manufacturing of sealants.\r\nThe Pasadena facility is equipped to safely unload tank trucks and railcars into storage vessels.  Access to the site is restricted to authorized facility personnel, management and contractors.\r\n\r\nC.  General accidental release prevention program and chemical-specific prevention steps:\r\n\r\nThe Kaneka facility is a PSM-covered facility and, as such, it has a viable and robust process safety program.  \r\nProcess Hazards Analyses have been conducted on processes containing all four RMP-covered chemicals.  Major hazards identified include fire, explosion, toxic chemical releases, overpressurization, overfilling, and equipment failure.  Process controls in place include relief valves, emergency and automatic shutdowns, grounding, interlocks and procedures and training.  Additionally, Acrylonitrile, Chlorine and Propylene Oxide storage are contained within dikes with appropriate drainage and fire protection.  Fire protection is also provided for areas containing the flammable chemical 1, 3-Butadiene.  \r\nTraining is conducted continuously by a dedicated training department and includes classroom, on-the-job mentoring and standard operating procedure (SOP) reviews.  Testing and demonstration are used as means to verify understanding.  SOPs are kep"
    },
    {
